## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Fatal at runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Fatal at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never raised | Dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire mid-`finally` block, leave locks held, and cause torn writes.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The delegate should observe the <see cref="CancellationToken"/> to stop promptly.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did.
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-throws as AggregateException, matching original behavior.
        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async overload — prefer this in new code.
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Synchronous — the work lambda observes the token.
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative exit point
        // ... do a chunk of work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Async
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

### Pitfalls to Watch For

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation does nothing if the delegate ignores the token. CPU-bound loops **must** call `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` periodically. Most BCL I/O APIs (`Stream.ReadAsync`, `HttpClient`, etc.) already accept tokens.

**2. Uncooperative/third-party code.**
If you truly can't modify the work delegate, isolate it in a **separate process** — not a thread. A thread cannot be safely killed in .NET 8. A thin wrapper:

```csharp
// Last resort for uncooperative code — fire-and-forget the thread.
// The work keeps running but the caller is unblocked.
public T ExecuteWithTimeoutUncooperative<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    T result = default;
    Exception error = null;

    var thread = new Thread(() =>
    {
        try { result = work(); }
        catch (Exception ex) { error = ex; }
    }) { IsBackground = true }; // won't block process exit

    thread.Start();

    if (!thread.Join(timeout))
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");

    if (error != null)
        throw new AggregateException(error);

    return result;
}
```

> ⚠️ This **leaks the thread** on timeout — it runs until completion or process exit. Acceptable only as a stopgap.

**3. `AggregateException` unwrapping.**
`Task.Result` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`, which matches your original code. If callers expect the inner exception directly, use `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` instead.

**4. `default(T)` behavioral change.**
Not migration-related, but `default` for non-nullable reference types in .NET 8 with nullable-analysis enabled will produce warnings. Consider `T? result` or `[return: MaybeNull]`.
